{
  "updated_summary": "Aleksandr Menkov, in a blue and pink Nike singlet, walks the track with focus, but a Red Flag Official signals a foul with a raised red flag at the white and blue takeoff board, resulting in Menkov's disappointment and a head shake; the scoreboard displays his results as 8.27m with two 'X's, marking his third foul attempt as he walks past the sandpit where a Man in Blue Hoodie with 'URUGUAY' sits among other athletes and officials. The commentator notes the 'absolutely packed' stadium, the 'huge support' from the Stadium Crowd, and the heightened competition level, anticipating a 'monstrous jump' from 'Man' (Luvo Manyonga) and Jarrion Lawson's strong position. The scene shifts to Michel Tornéus, the Swedish long jumper in a yellow 'SWEDEN' singlet, who begins his focused run-up under the bright stadium lights and the 'IAAF World Championships LONDON 2017' banner, with the SEIKO Countdown Timer ticking down; he executes his jump, landing in the sandpit with a splash, but the commentator notes that Tornéus "could produce a jump which gets him into the medal positions." Tornéus walks away with a disappointed expression as the commentator exclaims about a "massive jump," but a flag goes up again, indicating another foul, a "major disappointment," confirmed by the scoreboard showing his best valid jump of 8.18m and two previous fouls; a close-up reveals his yellow and red Nike shoe at the takeoff board with a 0.7m measurement, explaining the foul, and the commentator emphasizes the pressure of the "World Championship final," placing Tornéus in "seventh place." Emiliano Lasa of Uruguay, in a white singlet, then executes a powerful jump, landing in the sandpit, with the scoreboard displaying 8.06m, as the packed stadium generates a vibrant atmosphere with audible crowd noise under the bright lights of the Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park, with 'TOYOTA' and 'TDK' banners visible trackside, and the 'IAAF World Championships LONDON 2017' banner in the background, and a Female Official is seen near the sandpit. Lasa begins his run-up, and a distinct landing sound is heard as he leaps, with the White Flag Official raising a white flag, confirming a valid jump, which the commentator notes is "around about his best for the season," praising it as "a good jump from this man," and elaborating on the exceptionally high quality of the long jump final; the Scoreboard updates to 8.11m, a "slight improvement" that places him in ninth, and Lasa claps to the crowd, acknowledging their presence, as he walks confidently against the backdrop of TOYOTA, SEIKO, TDK, and Newham London banners."
}
